Project 1: Can Certain Release Points Lead to Greater Pitching Success in the MLB?

By: Jonathan Dietrich, Conner Toryfter & Karan Kapur

Executive Summary

In Major League Baseball, gaining a competitive edge on opponents through pitching relates to knowing what aspects allow a pitcher to be successful. For our project, we set out to explore whether a pitchers release point, the location where the ball leaves the pitchers hand, defined by its horizontal distance and vertical height from home plate, has any correlation with better performance. Our goal was to analyze key stats like Earned Run Average (ERA), Fielding Independent Pitching (FIP), Walks plus Hits per Inning Pitched (WHIP), and Strikeout-to-Walk ratio (K/BB), across various release points. Using 2025 MLB season data, we grouped pitchers based on their release points to see if certain release points lead to superior results, aiming to find an ideal release point range that would provide insights for player development and coaching, in the hope of developing more successful pitchers.

For our data, we used Baseball Reference and MLB Statcast, focusing on qualified pitchers who had pitched at least nine innings to ensure accurate sample sizes and exclude potential position players whose release points shouldnt be taken into account when comparing overall pitching in the MLB. We categorized them by whether their release points were higher or lower vertically and closer or further horizontally from home plate, forming groups like Right-Handed, Further, Higher or Left-Handed, Closer, Lower. Our analysis revealed that left-handed pitchers with release points further from home plate and higher vertically showed a slight edge, but not statistically significant when comparing across our four metrics, with an average ERA of around 3.80 compared to the leagues 4.00. Right-handed pitchers, however, didnt show as clear a trend.

Our findings deepen this exploration, indicating that for left-handed pitchers, a further and higher release point might optimize success, despite horizontal and vertical variations having minimal impact on ERA, WHIP, FIP, or K/BB%. This suggests that focusing player development on left-handers who throw from extended and elevated positions could enhance their MLB prospects, while scouts might prioritize such profiles for a slight performance boost. For right-handed pitchers, we noted marginally higher ERA and FIP, but shifts in horizontal and vertical release depths didnt significantly alter these stats. Notably, the standout group of left-handed pitchers, with a mean release distance exceeding 2.088 feet and height above 5.753 feet, included top performers like Trevor Rogers, who holds an impressive 1.81 ERA, and Garrett Crochet, a 2025 CY-Young candidate with a 2.59 ERA, highlighting that a potential ideal release point is similar to guys of this sort. However, when looking past the base metrics used to compare the pitchers, we found very little to no statistical significance to back whether a certain release point group was more successful. However, it was found that left-handed pitchers in general yield more success in the MLB in the metrics we dug into.

These insights can guide teams to refine pitching mechanics or scout for specific release point traits that align with success. Still, we recognize the need for more study, considering factors like pitch velocity or spin rate, and incorporating data from past seasons would only enhance our conclusions. Additionally, exploring how release points interact with a pitchers physical build or delivery style might reveal new advantages or even potential disadvantages, while testing these findings across different ballparks could uncover environmental influences. This broader approach could lead teams to more efficient development plans, ensuring a more comprehensive strategy for creating future pitching success.

Technical Summary

Data Collection

We wanted to look at data from all pitches during the 2025 MLB regular season. We used the modified version of Bill Pettis statcast scraper from lecture 6 to scrape the pitch by pitch data for the season. Because this code takes over an hour to run, we decided not to include it in this file, but saved the data as raw_statcast2025.RData, and loaded it in below. We then found the average x and z depth for each pitcher across all of their pitches for the season. Lastly, we used the bref_daily_pitcher function to scrape season long statistics for each pitcher from Baseball Reference, and joined this with the release data we had already.

Comparisons

We then wanted to compare how the different release points affected different statistics like ERA, WHIP, FIP and K/BB. The data did not have FIP so we calculated that ourselves. After, we split the data between left and right handed pitchers, and then grouped their releases into either further or closer, and higher or lower, creating 8 different release point groups. We then looked at how the ERA, WHIP, FIP, and K/BB changed across groups when we grouped by only handedness, only x_depth, only z_depth, and all of them together.

all_pitcher_stats = named_releases %>% left_join(bbref, by = "bbref_id") %>% group_by(throwing_hand) %>% mutate(x_depth = ifelse(abs(avg_rel_x) > abs(mean(avg_rel_x)), "Further", "Closer")) %>% mutate(z_depth = ifelse(avg_rel_z > mean(avg_rel_z), "Higher", "Lower")) %>% mutate(FIP = round(((13 * HR + (3 * (BB + HBP)) - (2 * SO)) / IP) + 3.14, 3))

nums4 = named_releases %>% left_join(bbref, by = "bbref_id") %>% group_by(throwing_hand) %>% summarize(x_avg = mean(avg_rel_x), z_avg = mean(avg_rel_z))

final_pitchers = all_pitcher_stats %>% select(Name.x, throwing_hand, IP, avg_rel_x, avg_rel_z, x_depth, z_depth, ERA, WHIP, FIP, SO.W) %>% filter(!is.na(ERA), !is.na(WHIP), !is.na(FIP), !is.na(SO.W)) %>% ungroup() %>% filter(IP > 9)

all_pitchers_means = final_pitchers %>% summarize(mean_era = mean(ERA), mean_whip = mean(WHIP), mean_fip = mean(FIP), mean_sow = mean(SO.W), count = n())

groupings = final_pitchers  %>% group_by(throwing_hand, x_depth, z_depth, avg_rel_x, avg_rel_z) %>% summarize(mean_era = mean(ERA), mean_whip = mean(WHIP), mean_fip = mean(FIP), mean_sow = mean(SO.W), count = n()) %>% mutate(Category = paste(x_depth, z_depth, throwing_hand))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'throwing_hand', 'x_depth', 'z_depth',
## 'avg_rel_x'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
grouped_by_hand = final_pitchers %>% ungroup() %>% group_by(throwing_hand) %>% summarize(mean_era = mean(ERA), mean_whip = mean(WHIP), mean_fip = mean(FIP), mean_sow = mean(SO.W), count = n())

grouped_by_xdepth = final_pitchers %>% ungroup() %>% group_by(x_depth) %>% summarize(mean_era = mean(ERA), mean_whip = mean(WHIP), mean_fip = mean(FIP), mean_sow = mean(SO.W), count = n())

grouped_by_zdepth = final_pitchers %>% ungroup() %>% group_by(z_depth) %>% summarize(mean_era = mean(ERA), mean_whip = mean(WHIP), mean_fip = mean(FIP), mean_sow = mean(SO.W), count = n())

combined_groups = final_pitchers  %>% group_by(throwing_hand, x_depth, z_depth) %>% summarize(mean_era = mean(ERA), mean_whip = mean(WHIP), mean_fip = mean(FIP), mean_sow = mean(SO.W), count = n()) %>% mutate(Category = paste(x_depth, z_depth, throwing_hand))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'throwing_hand', 'x_depth'. You can
## override using the `.groups` argument.
groupings_no_hand = final_pitchers  %>% group_by(x_depth, z_depth) %>% summarize(mean_era = mean(ERA), mean_whip = mean(WHIP), mean_fip = mean(FIP), mean_sow = mean(SO.W), count = n()) %>% mutate(Category = paste(x_depth, z_depth))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'x_depth'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Linear model

Finally, we created four linear models to test the statistical significance of our results. Each one we compared one of the four pitching metrics to throwing hand, x_depth, and z_depth.
